  "prompt": "How does the Zika Virus affect men and non pregnant women?",
  "response": "The Zika virus can affect both men and non-pregnant women, although the effects are generally less severe compared to its impact on pregnant women and their fetuses. Here\u2019s a detailed look at how Zika can affect men and non-pregnant women:\n\n### Symptoms in Men and Non-Pregnant Women\nMost people infected with the Zika virus won't have symptoms or will only have mild symptoms. When symptoms do occur, they typically appear 3-14 days after the bite of an infected mosquito and may include:\n- Fever\n- Rash\n- Headache\n- Joint pain\n- Conjunctivitis (red eyes)\n- Muscle pain\n\nThese symptoms are usually mild and last for several days to a week.\n\n### Complications\nWhile rare, some complications can occur in men and non-pregnant women:\n\n1. **Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome (GBS)**: A rare disorder where the body's immune system attacks the nerves. This can lead to muscle weakness and, in severe cases, paralysis. GBS requires hospitalization and can be life-threatening.\n\n2. **Neurological and Autoimmune Issues**: There have been reports of other neurological conditions and autoimmune issues linked to Zika, though these are less common and not as well understood.\n\n### Sexual Transmission\nMen infected with the Zika virus can transmit the virus to their sexual partners (male or female) through semen, even if they do not show symptoms. The virus can remain in semen longer than in other bodily fluids, sometimes for several months. Therefore, it's recommended for men to use condoms or abstain from sexual activity for at least six months after the onset of symptoms or their last possible exposure to Zika.\n\n### Long-Term Effects\nThere is still ongoing research about the long-term effects of Zika on men and non-pregnant women. While most recover fully, the potential for long-term neurological or autoimmune issues remains a concern.\n\n### Preventive Measures\nTo prevent Zika infection, men and non-pregnant women should:\n- Use insect repellent\n- Wear long-sleeved shirts and long pants\n- Stay in places with air conditioning or that use window and door screens to keep mosquitoes outside\n- Sleep under a mosquito net\n- Take precautions to prevent sexual transmission if their partner may have been exposed to Zika\n\nIn summary, while Zika can cause mild symptoms in men and non-pregnant women, the risk of severe complications like Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome exists. Preventive measures and awareness about sexual transmission are crucial in managing and preventing the spread of the virus.",
